s","id":"90304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90304"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old woman presents with a six month history of early satiety. She has no other symptoms and is otherwise well. Physical examination is unremarkable and a CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following structures are in their incorrect anatomical place?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stomach and liver","Liver and left kidney","Spleen and left kidney","Spleen and liver","Stomach and transverse colon"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a massive hiatus hernia. Without seeing its relationship to the oesophagus, it is difficult to be certain that this is a para-oesophageal hernia rather than a sliding hernia. The diaphragm is clearly visible, with a large defect in the midline. Para-oesophageal hernias are often asymptomatic and incidental findings on imaging. However, in this case the patient has early satiety, a well-recognised symptom associated with these hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe liver and spleen are clearly visible below the right and left hemidiaphragms. Likewise the right and left kidneys can be seen in their correct anatomical positions. Most of this patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Estomach, transverse colon\u003C/strong\u003E and omentum have protruded through the oesophageal hiatus and have become trapped above the diaphragm. On the scan (Image) the diaphragm is labelled A, the transverse colon labelled B and the stomach is labelled C.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic hiatus hernias are relatively common findings on abdominal CT examinations."],"references":["O\u0027Sullivan JW, Muntinga T, Grigg S, et al. Prevalence and outcomes of incidental imaging findings: umbrella review.BMJ 2018; 361:k2387."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions"